    "0.392804\n",
    "0.911128\n",
    "0.049866\n",
    "63.548178\n",
    "0.802290\n",
    "0.000187\n",
    "0.000022\n",
    "0.026593\n",
    "0.000001"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2886a94a-b130-47f0-9e5f-cbcc088bb4ac",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 2. Soil module"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1c3ab6b1-f822-4115-be21-b501481e8b1b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next, we want to turn off the soil module. For this the evapotranspiration and the infiltration have to be set to zero. This can be achieved by  \n",
    "having the entirety of the potential runoff be the actualised runoff. Setting beta to zero will multiply the runoof potential with one and thus  \n",
    "trigger the wanted result. To turn off the evapotranspiration the initial soil moisture should be set to zero. One can also give the permanent   \n",
    "wilting point a very high value to achieve a similar result. For comparison, these were the optimised values:  \n",
    "\n",
    "94.568525 \"sl0_dth\"\n",
    "\n",
    "432.979200 \"sl0_pwp\"\n",
    "\n",
    "148.866130 \"sl0_fcy\"\n",
    "\n",
    "2.659653 \"sl0_bt0\"\n",
    "\n",
    "One can see, that every value will change quite a bit and thus a much more different result is to be expected. This can be explained by the big impact,\n",
    "which plants have on the water balance in this case, because we are in Bavaria, where there is plenty of vegetation. The soil itself also seems to \n",
    "absorb a non negligible amount of water. The results of running this module off are the following:\n",
    "\n",
    "An objective value of 0.157\n",
    "\n",
    "A NSE of 0.843"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {
    "ba7446ab-957f-4611-bd9c-0c20bfdfb987.png": {
     "image/png": ""
    }
   },
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4a9b5846-a196-4216-987a-fc2b7ab02376",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![optimized_run.png](attachment:ba7446ab-957f-4611-bd9c-0c20bfdfb987.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "44fa7528-4659-4d26-a364-2ef1bef0ca39",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The graph shows bigger errors in the simulation for the peaks and a slow approachment of the simulation towards the obeserved discharge afterwards,\n",
    "while even undershooting it after a while. This reoccuring theme seems to stem from the fact, that no water is infiltrating the soil and thus has to \n",
    "runoff immediately, which leaves less water to runoff in the lon run, thus creating this undershoot effect."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {
    "1f8972d9-9b70-4e3b-83a7-96b6920c41c3.png": {
     "image/png": ""
    }
   },
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "15e87c77-7944-4ac7-bfbb-3f01e0119ce3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![de_convergence.png](attachment:1f8972d9-9b70-4e3b-83a7-96b6920c41c3.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "14c6c450-3dc5-44b8-9cc6-241cc20228ff",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Indeed, like expected, the convergence is less than optimal. The decent NSE and resulting objective function value seem to be a fluke. The graph \n",
    "seems to approach 0 several times, but quickly deteriorate quickly afterwards. It can be therefore assumed, that turning off the soil module will \n",
    "result in a bad simulation. Finally, the optimised values for the parameters:\n",
    "0.000000\n",
    "1.209218\n",
    "1.277700\n",
    "0.115713\n",
    "0.000000\n",
    "1000000.000000\n",
    "0.000001\n",
    "0.000000\n",
    "0.303784\n",
    "0.120041\n",
    "0.848500\n",
    "0.192323\n",
    "128.334607\n",
    "0.740068\n",
    "0.000190\n",
    "0.010203\n",
    "0.005468\n",
    "0.000916"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7bf7a99c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    " After the snow and soil components, the generated water enters the routing part of the HBV model, which is represented here through the upper reservoir and lower reservoir modules. These two reservoirs strongly control how water is stored, transferred, and finally released as discharge. For that reason, their parameters mainly influence the timing of runoff peaks, the speed of flow release, and the recession behaviour of the hydrograph.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fcac19f5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 3. Upper and Lower Reservoir Module"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ebc980dc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Turning the upper reservoir off\n",
    "\n",
    "When the upper reservoir is turned off, the direct fast-flow contribution from that module is removed. So water is no longer released through the upper-reservoir quickflow outlets, but is transferred downstream, so that the URR behaves mainly as a pass-through towards the lower reservoir. In the hbv model, this did not lead to a strong deterioration in model performance, which suggests that for the analysed time series the direct fast upper-reservoir contribution was not the dominant control on the hydrograph. Under the chosen settings and for the present period, suppressing the direct URR quickflow still allowed a comparatively good fit and we got a NSE of \n",
    "0.8874. \n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d8f8f8cf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "WSR = 0, \\qquad TDR = 0, \\qquad NDR = 0, \\qquad ULC = 1\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "and $URR_{TDH}$ is chosen sufficiently large, then\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "Q_T = 0, \\qquad Q_N = 0, \\qquad PLN = URR_{DTH}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Hence the upper reservoir no longer contributes direct runoff. Instead, the stored water is transferred onward to the lower reservoir. In this sense, the direct quickflow contribution of the URR is suppressed, and the URR behaves mainly as a pass-through storage.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {
    "Picture 1.png": {
     "image/png": ""
    }
   },
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "31e49a57",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![Picture 1.png](<attachment:Picture 1.png>)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "09cae5d2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Turning the lower reservoir off\n",
    "\n",
    "Turning off the lower reservoir removes the delayed storage-release component and therefore suppresses slow recession flow.\n",
    "\n",
    "If $$ DRE = 0 $$ then,\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "Q_L = LRR_{DTH} \\times 0 = 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "which means that the lower reservoir no longer contributes direct discharge to the hydrograph.\n",
    "\n",
    "The storage update then becomes\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "LRR_{DTH} \\leftarrow LRR_{DTH} - 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Hence the lower reservoir no longer contributes direct discharge.  \n",
    "It only stores the incoming \\(PLN\\), so it remains present in the model as storage, but not as an active outflow component. \n",
    "For our HBV model, turning the lower reservoir off gives a NSE of -0.1039\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
